The paper deals with distributed storage systems, specifically key-value stores, and discusses the tradeoff between consistency and latency. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. Additionally, the paper presents probabilistic models to characterize the three important elements of the CAP theorem, which suggests that it could also belong to the Databases (cs.DB) sub-category. The paper also discusses the design of a class of systems that adapt to meet SLAs while optimizing the consistency/latency tradeoff, which suggests that it could belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. The paper presents two CAP-like impossibility theorems, which suggests that it could also belong to the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the extension of the proposed system to multiple geo-distributed data-centers, which suggests that it could also belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category.
